    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-07-02T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-07-02T08:00:00-05:00" n="250"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d250">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.9315 Manchuria/2: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-07-02T16:00:00+03:00"
                            >July 2, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 2—11:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>261. My 259 and 260 of July 2nd.<note n="10" xml:id="d250fn10">Neither
                        printed.</note> The Soviet Government is apprehensive that the succession of
                    incidents on the Soviet-Manchurian <pb facs="0401" n="289" xml:id="pg_289"/>
                    frontier presages a demand from Japan for demilitarization of border zone and
                    the sale of the northern half of Sakhalin Island.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
